the instagram shitty feedback loop does damage beyond just poor engagement. 

if i don’t post anything, i feel like i’m not getting validation for my work or talent. in an attempt to grasp onto some creative self worth and some sense of feeling from years ago, i post. then the lack of engagement because of how instagram works makes me feel less then i did to begin with. this leads me to not posting, not having my work seen, not booking new work i’d be proud to make, not creating, and the cycle begins again. 

i got tremendously lucky being able to create work of a high standard pretty effortlessly for the most part. 

but being that photography has been my only successful creative outlet, it’s a struggle. i don’t creatively (or non-creatively) succeed in really many other kind of spaces in the way i do with a camera. 

this has been a big talking point in therapy for years for me, but i can’t say i’ve ever come to a conclusion other than acceptance that maybe i creatively peaked. i had a good run of a couple of years jetting around, seeing the world that i hadn’t had the means to see before, sharing my work and partaking a little too heavy into the drug of internet points. 

my confidence had always been less than ideal making me such a prime candidate for tying my self worth to words of affirmations from strangers. this has been my life’s most damaging addiction and the rehab for it is daunting, seemingly endless and i’ve come out the other side far worse off than i started. 

to accept adequate when faux exceptionalism is as much a part of our world as the air we breath, feels impossible. 
.

.

oh instagram, our endless battles continue. i took a deactivation break this week for the first time, which motivated me to build some specific daytime and evening focus routines on my phone to work on limiting the amount of notifications that scream for attention from me. i really think using my phone as an escape from momentary boredom has a much larger negative effect overall. on the way i process downtime, dopamine levels and not allowing myself to become creative or inventive in the middle of boredom.

i’ve always had an issue with when/how/what volume social media plays in my world. for a while when i stopped using stories & close friends altogether i noticed a change in my real life social circle. like it or not, stories & the interaction that surround them are currency in our social economy. so many of my plans come together because of some series of messages or interactions with friends about what they’re doing that day, a show we’re going to or a random trip to the lake on our bikes. when i removed this singular line of communication a lot of that started to break down. 

i’ve never had a truly personal instagram where i posted low-effort photos of myself, a trip, things i was interested in or memories with friends. since close to the beginning it’s always been used as a tool in my creative career. despite all that i still find my muscle memory bringing me to open instagram even when i don’t mean to. endlessly bouncing between ig, reddit, ig, reddit, ig, reddit, ad infinitum.

[continued in comments]

for years i’ve been imagining what kind of conversation would surround the mentioning of my name in a car ride amongst my friends. for the longest time and so many sessions in therapy i would point to the empty chair in the office and imagine a version of myself sitting there, shutting the fuck up. if i could just manage to shut the fuck up, maybe the imaginary car ride conversation would change from feeling like people thought i was abrasive, too much, too insultive or sarcastic to something more simple and kind. 

i worked on this feeling for so long that i’ve felt like i lost a piece of myself. i’m less than i was, or too quiet. not enough personality to break the surface of social situations and no where to feel fully all of myself.

i’ve always been described as wearing my heart on my sleeve, but as i’ve gotten older i’ve leaned into being vulnerable. i’ve leaned into feeling like my own self-development was something that was worth sharing. when i’m struggling i’m an external processor, leaning on my people to provide me invaluable insight into my well being. 

but now i feel like it’s too much. i feel like i’m the friend who’s always struggling with something, or working through an issue. always working on myself and always in a place people need to be concerned for me. the imaginary car ride has become people feeling pity for me. translating into real life perceptions of feeling like the tagalong friend or pity invite.

my dear friend @alexjanvrin told me “as my friend, your well being is part my responsibility” and the same of i for her. we have a secure attachment and never find ourself in a form of protest behavior to get a response out of the other. i’ve always felt that feeling of responsibility for my people, but believed like i should be self sufficient in my own feelings. i’m trying to learn that the people in my life are supposed to make me feel secure, they are supposed to hear my emotions and hold them with care and responsibility. 

there is a spot between feeling too abrasive, feeling too quiet and not my whole self and feeling too much of a burden to the people around me. 

i am trying to get there.

instagram really seems to be my journal lately. swipe to hear me whine

i’ve definitely lost that creative spark for personal projects. i’m not sure when it happened. if it’s the monotony of setting up a shoot, creating self imposed deadlines to finish it, sharing it and the internet not really caring or something else altogether. 

its frustrating knowing how talented i can be when i want to, but the overall idea of it feels like a chore. 

creating has been a part of my identity for years and to not feel attracted to it feels a bit like not being attracted to a piece of myself. 

i’m not sure if i need a new challenge, a different format, a new end objective (or simply one to begin with) or finding acceptance in allowing myself to fall further and further from it all.

monday. there was probably a monday where i felt confident but that feels like forever ago. i haven’t been confident in literally so long and i’ve been trying so damn hard to address it, but i’m really hitting wall after wall lately. so i guess i’ll whine about it on instagram so i can distract myself with the shame and pity of that choice for a few hours instead.
is it running on auto pilot if it still takes all the energy in the world just to keep my nose above the water?

been thinking a lot about the kind of content and life i share on instagram. microjupiter has been my alias for over 20 years now. from xbox live to when i competed in halo 3 for @mlgofficial, then to my wedding career and now just as intertwined with my identity as my given name. 

i make photos all of the time that have never felt like they have a home since this account has been solely weddings or portrait work for so long, limiting myself from the large variety of things i love or am inspired by. piles of images made from the things i see out in the world, rolls and rolls of film that span professional art as well as visual journals of my life that no one ever really sees aside from the occasional instagram story i make on a whim or my brief use of @tothedepthsofatlantis. i think it’s time to change that to allow this page, a place with my name stamped at the top and an associated tattoo on my body to not be limited to a singular kind of art. 

i might change my mind next week, or even in an hour. but for now, here’s me and my bike francesca, a bianchi chrome pista i found and fell in love with last year while on the quest to focus on more movement and physical activity. #bianchi #cycling #5

in my quest for understanding my shit self confidence that took a dramatic nosedive at the beginning of 2020 i’ve landed on a feeling i didn’t even realize i was experiencing. 

i’m afraid of some silly stuff. the red bridge on damen/elston because one time i rode my bike on it and it kicked my ass. or riding the north branch trail because the first time i tried it i could barely do 10 miles. finding myself afraid of an outcome that only happened once and has proven itself incorrect time and time again. i can feel myself getting nervous for a short ride just because years and years of experiences prior where i wasn’t able to do it or was the slow friend in the back desperately trying to keep up with everyone else as they handled it with ease. 

i’m fearful before a lot of social situations in the last couple of years. some circles or people more than others, but almost always some amount regardless. fearful i wont be interesting enough or bring value to the conversation. fearful i’ll be too much, too quiet, too out of touch or too unbecoming. such a small percentage of the time does any of that ever come close to truth but my belief system is so tied up in the feeling rather than the actuality. 

for someone whose been pretty pragmatic and evidence based in my feelings or outcomes of my feelings, realizing how absolutely wrong i’ve been is pretty jarring but it does feel good to have a specific word to define my feelings or actions leading into situations that make me feel small. 

i believe i am less than enough and undeserving of even my own love because i’m basing that belief on outcomes driven by fear that rarely ever come into existence. how fucking silly is that. 

how many things am i not allowing myself to make, experience or participate in because fear drives me away from it?
neon ruins

what parts of the human experience have you not been able to participate in?

how can i ever begin to change the outcomes im disappointed in if i don’t ever change my approach? 

how can i change an approach when an entire belief system says otherwise?

i eased off the gas some time ago and 2023 has felt like the last act of a written story; conclusions to main story lines, rest & relaxation for the protagonist and cast of characters, new beginnings while simultaneously rounding out some of the goals set forth the year prior. plot lines i expected to go one direction surprised me with new beginnings i never could have predicted. 

2024 is open ended, undecided and with no certain course. gravity seems to be reaching out to pull the peddle closer to the floor again, the universe whispering to allow my ambition to take the lead again.
